<li id="cite_note-254"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="Hinduism#cite_ref-254">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><cite id="CITEREFNeville2001" class="citation book">Neville, Robert (2001). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://books.google.com/books?id=ThLR13JpCWsC"><i>Religious truth</i></a>. p.&#160;51. <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISBN_(identifier)" class="mw-redirect" title="ISBN (identifier)">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Special:BookSources/978-0-7914-4778-9" title="Special:BookSources/978-0-7914-4778-9"><bdi>978-0-7914-4778-9</bdi></a>. <q>Mimamsa theorists (theistic and atheistic) decided that the evidence allegedly proving the existence of God was insufficient. They also thought there was no need to postulate a maker for the world, just as there was no need for an author to compose the Veda or an independent God to validate the Vedic rituals.</q></cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Religious+truth&amp;rft.pages=51&amp;rft.date=2001&amp;rft.isbn=978-0-7914-4778-9&amp;rft.aulast=Neville&amp;rft.aufirst=Robert&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.com%2Fbooks%3Fid%3DThLR13JpCWsC&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AHinduism" class="Z3988"></span><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r951705291"/></span>
