<li id="cite_note-306"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="Hinduism#cite_ref-306">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><cite id="CITEREFOlivelle2014" class="citation book"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Patrick_Olivelle" title="Patrick Olivelle">Olivelle, Patrick</a> (2014). <i>The Early Upanisads</i>. Oxford University Press. p.&#160;3. <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISBN_(identifier)" class="mw-redirect" title="ISBN (identifier)">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Special:BookSources/978-0-19-535242-9" title="Special:BookSources/978-0-19-535242-9"><bdi>978-0-19-535242-9</bdi></a>. <q>Even though theoretically the whole of vedic corpus is accepted as revealed truth [shruti], in reality it is the Upanishads that have continued to influence the life and thought of the various religious traditions that we have come to call Hindu. Upanishads are the scriptures par excellence of Hinduism</q></cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=The+Early+Upanisads&amp;rft.pages=3&amp;rft.pub=Oxford+University+Press&amp;rft.date=2014&amp;rft.isbn=978-0-19-535242-9&amp;rft.aulast=Olivelle&amp;rft.aufirst=Patrick&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AHinduism" class="Z3988"></span><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r951705291"/></span>
