<li id="cite_note-440"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="Hinduism#cite_ref-440">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><cite id="CITEREFOlcott1906" class="citation book">Olcott, HS (1906). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://books.google.com/books?id=jKBVAAAAYAAJ&amp;pg=PA146"><i>The Theosophist</i></a>. <b>XXVII</b>. Theosophical Publishing House. pp.&#160;146 with footnote.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=The+Theosophist&amp;rft.pages=146+with+footnote&amp;rft.pub=Theosophical+Publishing+House&amp;rft.date=1906&amp;rft.aulast=Olcott&amp;rft.aufirst=HS&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.com%2Fbooks%3Fid%3DjKBVAAAAYAAJ%26pg%3DPA146&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AHinduism" class="Z3988"></span><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r951705291"/>, Quote: "It is well known that Vaishnavas abhor animal sacrifice. In this province, like nearly all Bengalis, they celebrate Durga Puja, but their ceremonies are bloodless".</span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-FOOTNOTEFuller2004101–102,_Quote:_&quot;Blood_sacrifice_was_a_clear_case_in_point,_(,,,)_sacrifice_was_a_barbarity_inconsistent_with_Hinduism&#39;s_central_tenet_of_non-violence._&#91;...&#93;_Contemporary_opposition_to_animal_sacrifice_rests_on_an_old_foundation,_although_it_also_stems_from_the_very_widespread_influence_of_reformism,_whose_antipathy_to_ritual_killing_has_spread_well_beyond_the_self-consciously_nationalist_political_classes&quot;.-441"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="Hinduism#cite_ref-FOOTNOTEFuller2004101–102,_Quote:_&quot;Blood_sacrifice_was_a_clear_case_in_point,_(,,,)_sacrifice_was_a_barbarity_inconsistent_with_Hinduism&#39;s_central_tenet_of_non-violence._[...]_Contemporary_opposition_to_animal_sacrifice_rests_on_an_old_foundation,_although_it_also_stems_from_the_very_widespread_influence_of_reformism,_whose_antipathy_to_ritual_killing_has_spread_well_beyond_the_self-consciously_nationalist_political_classes&quot;._441-0">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><a href="Hinduism#CITEREFFuller2004">Fuller 2004</a>, pp.&#160;101–102, Quote: "Blood sacrifice was a clear case in point, (,,,) sacrifice was a barbarity inconsistent with Hinduism's central tenet of non-violence. [...] Contemporary opposition to animal sacrifice rests on an old foundation, although it also stems from the very widespread influence of reformism, whose antipathy to ritual killing has spread well beyond the self-consciously nationalist political classes"..</span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-442"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="Hinduism#cite_ref-442">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><cite id="CITEREFNicholson2010" class="citation book">Nicholson, Andrew J. (2010). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://books.google.com/books?id=fv4rtMlLv3kC"><i>Unifying Hinduism: Philosophy and Identity in Indian Intellectual History</i></a>. Columbia University Press. p.&#160;169. <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISBN_(identifier)" class="mw-redirect" title="ISBN (identifier)">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Special:BookSources/978-0-231-14986-0" title="Special:BookSources/978-0-231-14986-0"><bdi>978-0-231-14986-0</bdi></a>.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Unifying+Hinduism%3A+Philosophy+and+Identity+in+Indian+Intellectual+History&amp;rft.pages=169&amp;rft.pub=Columbia+University+Press&amp;rft.date=2010&amp;rft.isbn=978-0-231-14986-0&amp;rft.aulast=Nicholson&amp;rft.aufirst=Andrew+J.&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.com%2Fbooks%3Fid%3Dfv4rtMlLv3kC&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AHinduism" class="Z3988"></span><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r951705291"/>, Quote: "The acceptance of the principle of nonviolence has been so through that animal sacrifice among Hindus today is uncommon, and many Indians are of the opinion that such things as cow slaughter were never practiced in ancient India".</span>
</li>
