<li id="cite_note-572"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="Hinduism#cite_ref-572">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><cite id="CITEREFJayatilleke2010" class="citation book">Jayatilleke, KN (2010). <i>Early Buddhist Theory of Knowledge</i>. pp.&#160;246–249, from note 385 onwards. <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISBN_(identifier)" class="mw-redirect" title="ISBN (identifier)">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Special:BookSources/978-81-208-0619-1" title="Special:BookSources/978-81-208-0619-1"><bdi>978-81-208-0619-1</bdi></a>;</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Early+Buddhist+Theory+of+Knowledge&amp;rft.pages=246-249%2C+from+note+385+onwards&amp;rft.date=2010&amp;rft.isbn=978-81-208-0619-1&amp;rft.aulast=Jayatilleke&amp;rft.aufirst=KN&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AHinduism" class="Z3988"></span><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r951705291"/><br /><cite id="CITEREFCollins1994" class="citation book">Collins, Steven (1994).  Reynolds, Frank; Tracy, David (eds.). <i>Religion and Practical Reason</i>. State Univ of New York Press. p.&#160;64. <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISBN_(identifier)" class="mw-redirect" title="ISBN (identifier)">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Special:BookSources/978-0-7914-2217-5" title="Special:BookSources/978-0-7914-2217-5"><bdi>978-0-7914-2217-5</bdi></a>. <q>Central to Buddhist soteriology is the doctrine of not-self (Pali: anattā, Sanskrit: anātman, the opposed doctrine of <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/%C4%80tman_(Hinduism)" title="Ātman (Hinduism)">ātman</a> is central to Brahmanical thought). Put very briefly, this is the [Buddhist] doctrine that human beings have no soul, no self, no unchanging essence.</q></cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Religion+and+Practical+Reason&amp;rft.pages=64&amp;rft.pub=State+Univ+of+New+York+Press&amp;rft.date=1994&amp;rft.isbn=978-0-7914-2217-5&amp;rft.aulast=Collins&amp;rft.aufirst=Steven&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AHinduism" class="Z3988"></span><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r951705291"/>;<br /><cite class="citation book"><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://books.google.com/books?id=3uwDAAAAMAAJ&amp;pg=PA2"><i>Shankara's Introduction</i></a>. Translated by Roer, Edward. pp.&#160;2–4.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Shankara%27s+Introduction&amp;rft.pages=2-4&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.com%2Fbooks%3Fid%3D3uwDAAAAMAAJ%26pg%3DPA2&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AHinduism" class="Z3988"></span><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r951705291"/><br /><cite id="CITEREFJavanaud2013" class="citation web">Javanaud, Katie (2013). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://philosophynow.org/issues/97/Is_The_Buddhist_No-Self_Doctrine_Compatible_With_Pursuing_Nirvana">"Is The Buddhist 'No-Self' Doctrine Compatible With Pursuing Nirvana?"</a>. <i>Philosophy Now</i>.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.jtitle=Philosophy+Now&amp;rft.atitle=Is+The+Buddhist+%27No-Self%27+Doctrine+Compatible+With+Pursuing+Nirvana%3F&amp;rft.date=2013&amp;rft.aulast=Javanaud&amp;rft.aufirst=Katie&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fphilosophynow.org%2Fissues%2F97%2FIs_The_Buddhist_No-Self_Doctrine_Compatible_With_Pursuing_Nirvana&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AHinduism" class="Z3988"></span><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r951705291"/></span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-573"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="Hinduism#cite_ref-573">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><cite id="CITEREFPlott2000" class="citation book">Plott, John C.;  et al. (2000). <i>Global History of Philosophy: The Axial Age</i>. <b>1</b>. Motilal Banarsidass. p.&#160;63. <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISBN_(identifier)" class="mw-redirect" title="ISBN (identifier)">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Special:BookSources/978-81-208-0158-5" title="Special:BookSources/978-81-208-0158-5"><bdi>978-81-208-0158-5</bdi></a>. <q>The Buddhist schools reject any Ātman concept. As we have already observed, this is the basic and ineradicable distinction between Hinduism and Buddhism</q></cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Global+History+of+Philosophy%3A+The+Axial+Age&amp;rft.pages=63&amp;rft.pub=Motilal+Banarsidass&amp;rft.date=2000&amp;rft.isbn=978-81-208-0158-5&amp;rft.aulast=Plott&amp;rft.aufirst=John+C.&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AHinduism" class="Z3988"></span><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r951705291"/>.</span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-574"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="Hinduism#cite_ref-574">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">For the impact of "soul exists" concept in later Hinduism, see <cite class="citation book"><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://books.google.com/books?id=3uwDAAAAMAAJ&amp;pg=PA2"><i>Shankara's Introduction</i></a>. Translated by Roer, Edward. pp.&#160;3–4. <q>[...] Lokayatikas and Bauddhas who assert that the soul does not exist. There are four sects among the followers of Buddha: 1. Madhyamicas who maintain all is void; 2. Yogacharas, who assert except sensation and intelligence all else is void; 3. Sautranticas, who affirm actual existence of external objects no less than of internal sensations; 4. Vaibhashikas, who agree with later (Sautranticas) except that they contend for immediate apprehension of exterior objects through images or forms represented to the intellect.</q></cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Shankara%27s+Introduction&amp;rft.pages=3-4&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.com%2Fbooks%3Fid%3D3uwDAAAAMAAJ%26pg%3DPA2&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AHinduism" class="Z3988"></span><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r951705291"/></span>
</li>
